    body: "Cloister (from the Latin claustrum, 'enclosure') refers both to the physical space within a monastery or convent restricted to members of the community and to the juridical norm of enclosure that governs their separation from the world. Papal cloister, the strictest form, requires that contemplative nuns remain within the monastery and that outsiders not enter the enclosure except in specific circumstances. The tradition is rooted in the conviction that withdrawal from worldly distractions enables deeper prayer and intercession for the Church and the world. Pope Pius XII's Sponsa Christi (1950) and the Vatican II decree Perfectae Caritatis both addressed the adaptation of cloister norms while preserving their essential purpose.",
    example: "The Carmelite nuns of Compiegne, who were martyred during the French Revolution in 1794, maintained their cloistered life of prayer until the very end, going to the guillotine singing the Salve Regina — an event immortalized in Gertrud von Le Fort's novel and Poulenc's opera.",
    whyItMatters: "Cloistered life is the Church's hidden powerhouse of intercessory prayer, embodying the conviction that contemplation is not escapism but the most radical service to a world in need of God.",
