    body: "The title of basilica is a papal honor conferred on churches of exceptional importance. There are two categories: major basilicas and minor basilicas. The four major basilicas are all in Rome: St. Peter's, St. John Lateran (the Pope's cathedral as Bishop of Rome), St. Mary Major, and St. Paul Outside the Walls. They enjoy unique privileges and are associated with a papal altar and holy door. Minor basilicas are churches throughout the world to which the Pope has granted the title in recognition of their antiquity, dignity, historical significance, or role as pilgrimage centers. Basilicas display special insignia: the tintinnabulum (a bell on a pole) and the ombrellino (a half-opened umbrella in papal colors).",
